source.instructions:
**Assume the following code:**

```python-hide-clipboard
if my_var < 1:
    print("my_var is less than 1")
if my_var == 1:
    print("my_var is 1")
if my_var > 1:
    print("my_var is greater than 1")
```

**Drag the code blocks into the box below to create an equivalent program that uses elif statements instead of if statements. ++Hint++, not all of the code blocks will be used.**

source.initial:
if my_var &lt; 1:
    print(&quot;my_var is less than 1&quot;)
elif my_var == 1:
    print(&quot;my_var is 1&quot;)
else:
    print(&quot;my_var is greater than 1&quot;)
else my_var &gt; 1:  #distractor
else if my_var == 1:  #distractor

source.guidance:
All of the print statements are correct, so they can all be used. The `if` statement should be first, followed by the `elif` statement. `elif` is an abbreviation for `else if`, so the statement with `else if` can be ignored. Finally, the program should end with `else`, which does not require a boolean expression.

```python-hide-clipboard
if my_var < 1:
    print("my_var is less than 1")
elif my_var == 1:
    print("my_var is 1")
else:
    print("my_var is greater than 1")
```
